Vasco Chaya SENIOR WRITER chayav@dailynews.co.zw DENDERA star Suluman “Sulu” Chimbetu has temporarily shelved his guitar to focus on farming due to the inactivity in the music sector brought about by the Covid-19 pandemic. Since last March, Zimbabwe has been in a lockdown as authorities try to stop the spread of the deadly respiratory disease. As a result of the restrictions, all public gatherings and music concerts have been banned with stiff fines and jail sentences imposed on all violators. Most local musicians are now depending heavily on live shows to earn a living since they no longer make much income from sales due to piracy. The income from digital sales is also not enough to ensure local musicians can enjoy a comfortable lifestyle either. As a result of the depressed income from music under the lockdown, Sulu is now concentrating on his farming activities. At the moment, the Sean Timba hitmaker, is attending to his maize and bean crop at the Chegutu farm he inherited from his late father Simon. “Over the years, my brother was the one operating the farm but due to Covid-19 national lockdown, I am here full time and I am expecting a good harvest. Farming is an interesting venture. All that is needed is passion,” Sulu told the Daily News.  In December, Sulu, who joined showbiz in 2005 after serving in the Air Force of Zimbabwe, launched his latest album Entanglement at Mwanga Lodge, 40km along Shamva Road from the capital. Sulu had to settle for an online launch of the album with a limited number of attendees in line with Covid-19 regulations. He is not the only local musician who has been forced to venture into a different field during this lockdown. Afro-fusion song bird Diana Samkange aka Mangwenya is also holed up at her farm where she is concentrating on growing herbs. “The situation in the arts sector is deplorable. Musicians are suffering as the majority of them survived solely on concerts and royalties. As for me, I have diverted my attention and focus to farming and herb business,” Samkange said. Covid-19 has come with a huge demand for home-made remedies and Samkange is taking advantage of the ready market. “Since last year, I have recorded good business with clients buying Zumbani and other herbs to protect themselves against the virus. “The demand for Zumbani is too high. I am now spending most of my time in the jungle gathering traditional medicines for me to meet the demand,” Samkange said. Sponsored Links

    
      
        
          
